description.text:
A simple, detachable mount for your GoPro HERO Session that doubles as a battery strap buckle. This allows you to remove your GoPro easily when it's time to race!

We designed this for the Theory 250 frame but it can be used with any top mounted battery!

To complete the assembly, just wrap your GoPro in 1/4" thick adhesive-backed insulation foam which can be found at any home improvement store like Lowes, Home Depot, etc. Don't forget to put a little square on the back too. Insert your foam-wrapped GoPro into the mount and strap it down to the top of your battery. The compressed foam will dampen vibrations, protect your GoPro in a crash, and hold it securely until you push it back out.

The mount angle is 35º to keeps the props out of the shot while maintaining a view of the horizon in level flight and aggressive forward flight. With the Theory 250 quadcopter shown, no props are visible even in ultra-wide Superview mode. On some other quads though, it may be necessary to use standard 1080p mode or attach the mount at the front of the quad.

Don't forget that you can also tuck your balance connector under the mount.

Savinase is a serine protease, that you probably all seen in action. This is due to its wide use as an enzyme in detergents. Proteases are amazing enzymes breaking down other proteins into smaller and smaller chunks. Savinase does this by hydrolysing the peptide bonds that bind the aminoacids of proteins together. It does this by using a catalytic triade, where three aminoacids form a charge relay to make a powerful nucleophilic attack on peptide bonds.
In savinase, aspartate32 is hydrogenbonded to histidine64 thereby increasing the pKa of the imidazole-ring considerably. This in turn makes histidine a strong enough base to deprotonate serine221, which then attacks and breaks the peptide bond of a bound substrate. Even though the asp, his and ser residues are quite far apart in the backbone of savinase, the specific 3D folding of the protein brings them close enough together to enable their catalytic function. Substrates are bound in the ridge that is easily found in the printed structure. In this surface render, only the histidine and serine residues are visible (as seen on the pictures), the aspartate lies deeper in the enzyme just behind the histidine (indicated by the purple dots). NB. the model does not contain any color information - I crave a multi-color upgrade of my reprappro badly!

My family loves Pokémon Go, so we just had to have the game represented in the coming holiday seasons. I made this PokeStop Ornament in OpenSCAD and printed it in ColorFabb PLA/PHA (Sky Blue). This ornament won't deliver potions or Pokeballs, but it will spin just like the real thing!

If your "To Print" list is too long, you don't have the right color filament, or if the model is giving you a hassle, you can alternatively get a print on Etsy at https://www.etsy.com/listing/481786145/3d-printed-spinning-pokestop-ornament

I had a lot of fun getting this ornament together. Enjoy!

Edit Someone request smoother cylinders, there is a new STL named PokeStopIncreasedNumberOfFaces.stl that will give smoother outside edges. This version has not been personally tested by me as of 20170425. - VSS

Notes:

Because this ornament spins, you want the bottom to look just as good as it does on the top. It is worth the time to nail that first layer. If you have to err on your first layer being too close or two far away, I have found "too close" to be a more aesthetic choice.

There are small, 1mm thick placeholders outside of the moving pieces to help keep them in place. You may want to slow your first layer down slower than usual to help out those small details. My first layer speed was about 24mm/sec.

If you see those little 1mm placeholders fusing into the circles on the first layer, you don't necessary have to abort the print. Watch it a little bit. If subsequent layers have a gap, then it is typically easy to free the pieces with even just a fingernail when the print is done.

OpenSCAD

This ornament was designed in OpenSCAD. The design takes advantage of bridging. There is a little axis going through the center of the ornament. The axis is a simple 8-sided cylinder which is rotated to encourage bridging and to make sure we are using 45% overhangs.

All my clearences are 0.75mm. This was to allow for a super easy spin and to help prevent fusing on the first layers.

description.text: Whipped this up with boilermaker pride. Two files for two different font styles.
Print, place upon shelf.

For me, one of the "killer apps" for Kindle has been the text to speech feature. I spend enough time in the car commuting that I get a lot of "reading" done, and can carry forward in the other small snippets of spare time when I'm not driving or working.  
The Kindle Touch is one of the few models remaining (or only) which does this. Starting and stopping playback by finding the right "buttons" is hard.  
This frame fits snugly around the top and bottom of the device. The "telegraph keys" should accurately hit the spots to activate the menu, start text to speech, and stop text to speech. This makes it actually possible to stop it from reading totally without eye contact.  
The "hoops" are meant to keep papers and other things I may put on the passenger seat from sliding over the touch screen (which uses IR interferometry and is thus triggered by the lightest touch from any random object). These are currently prone to break off (as shown in the gallery - this suffered a drop with the Kindle inside) but the unit can be used to hit the menu buttons without them.

Print the top and bottom sections, taking care to avoid warping (avoid drafts, use heated bed, fresh coat of hairspray / ABS juice / whatever... you get the idea). Using a fine layer thickness (like 0.2mm or less) will help with printing the arched hoops.  
The clips will also be stronger if printed with a fine layer thickness.  
Print 2 of the "telegraph key" parts, which are already rotated in the best orientation for printing (flat side down).  
The "telegraph keys" are press-fitted onto the posts on the top and bottom parts as shown in the gallery pictures.  
The top "key" should hit the spot for activating the menu and the lower "key" should either select the menu item to start text to speech, or the button to stop text to speech playback.  
Freecad source included with guide objects - note that the actual spacing of the top and bottom parts is a bit closer than in the model.

description.text:
This holder is intended to hold a nexus 5x attached to a ProClip swivel mount or another mount with a standard AMPS mounting pattern. You should note that there is no stop at the bottom of the holder. Instead, the tab at the bottom has an array of small holes.

The idea is to use that tab and Sugru or similar to permanently affix a charging cable to the holder as a bottom stop for the phone, which you can see in the photo. (ignore the weird lens flare on the screen)

With the phone in the holder, most of the sides and back exposed, which is important to manage heat when you're streaming music and running GPS at the same time. It also leaves all of the controls, the mic, speakers, and headphone jack exposed so you can use them if you don't have a BT head unit. Even if you do have a BT head unit, being able to easily access the fingerprint scanner on the back or turn on your camera while it's in the mount can be handy as well.

Pretty straight forward print. 2 shells are probably enough, but I went with 3 since it will take some abuse living on my dash.

The dimensions are perfect if your printer is perfect and your plastic doesn't shrink at all. Obviously, you'll have to scale slightly if you print in ABS. I went up 2% and it was too much. 1% is probably enough for a print this size but YMMV.

If you scale it up to compensate for ABS shrinkage and find that you miss the mark a little, just hit the sides with a heat gun (or a small torch if you're REALLY careful) then slip the phone in and bend the sides in or out as needed (slowly and carefully)

POWER!!!

Any cable and charger will work, but I used the following since it meant more clearance and super fast charging, plus a clean look.

Charger (wired in behind the dash) https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00BMIVFK8/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o09_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1

Cable https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B0198806DU/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o00_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1

...and of course, the Sugru if you're unfamiliar https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00EU7DBNM/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o00_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1

With that combination, you can run the wire back into the dash (you can see in the photo where I ran it into the gap between the stereo and center console trim on my car) and get a very clean look that leaves your cigarette lighter socket available for other devices or to charge a passenger's phone.

ProClip (which is awesome in general) charges about $90 for a holder for this phone with tilt swivel and a hard-wired charging setup, and even then it's only 2amp, which means no rapid charging over USB-C.

If you make your own, you're out about $1 for plastic, $7.50 for the power converter, $5.50 for the cable, $15.50 for the Sugru(which will leave you with lots of extra packets of Sugru for other projects) and $19.99 for the tilt swivel.

Altogether, you get the same thing for just over half the cost. If you've already got Sugru laying around from other projects, and/or already have a tilt-swivel adapter from a previous ProClip holder (or you're using a different AMPS compatible mount) then you're really looking at 1/4 or less of the cost for the ProClip holder.

description.text:
Inspired from Kreg True-FLEX™ Featherboards

There are two versions, « TF_Featherboard_Easy_to_print.stl » is easier to print but need a little more material (~15%).

« TF_Featherboard.stl » need less material, but is a little harder to print (warping, stringing,...) and longer. Use it if your printer is well adjusted. Use 100% infill for this one. Support are optionals, but helps for the hoverang sections.

You can print many featherboard and stack them, just use two « TF_Spacer.stl » between each. You can stack 2, 3, 4... or more featherboards, usefull for resawing big parts on a bandsaw for example.

For T-Track/T-Slot you can use a 1/4-20 hex bolt, the lenght depend of how many featherboard you stack.

For miter gauge track, I provide an 'adapter' that works with 1/4-20 hex bolts too

Also, I designed a knob for a 1/4-20 nut.

Print with tought material (abs, petg,...), remember it is a safety part !

des pirates (海賊, kaizoku) de la région de Kumano, à qui ils doivent les techniques d'utilisation des grappins,
des yamabushi, ascètes vivant dans la montagne et adeptes du shugendō (pratiques mystiques),
des moines bouddhistes de la région, notamment des bouddhistes ésotériques shingon,
et des hinin, personnes de basse condition sociale utilisées pour les tâches jugées impures, notamment en relation avec le sang et le cuir.

Ninja (忍者) est un terme japonais moderne (xxe siècle), servant à désigner une certaine catégorie d'espions, actifs jusqu'à la période d'Edo (xviie siècle).

Le ninja désigne usuellement celui qui suit et achève la formation au ninjutsu (忍術), une discipline extrêmement rigoureuse tournée vers la survie, appliquée lors des périodes guerrières du Japon médiéval, aux missions d'espionnage, de renseignement, d'infiltration et de sabotage.

description.text:
My previous printable spring has an annoying tendency to break, this is the result of me trying to solve that problem.

In this spring every layer is made out of continuous and long strands of plastic, this makes it very strong and durable.

When printing set your shell width to at least half of the spring's lines (outerRadius minus innerRadius in the customizer, 2mm in the STL) this will make the spring all shells and that is what makes it work.

I tested it in ABS and PETG and it worked really well (PETG seems to be more durable), didn't try with PLA yet.

title: AA Cell Battery Box with Snap Lid, 1x AA to 4x AA Sizes

description.text:
These battery boxes have been designed with the intention that you will incorporate them into your project's 3d design directly, or you could simply cut a hole in your project and glue them in.

Each box is in 3 parts, the box itself, the lid section, and the catch which gets glued onto the lid. The catch is a separate piece because you need to print it "side on" so that the filament lies along the profile of the catch, otherwise it would just snap along the layers when you use it.

Be sure to print the box with support touching build plate only, printing support in the tab or catch receptacle would be hard to remove

Each box has a 5mm lip around the edge (actually 7mm but the inside 2mm is a fillet for strength) if you want to cut or design a hole and just glue in a separately printed box to your project.

I used CA glue (superglue) to glue the catch to the lid, works just fine. NB: Printed in PLA.

The positive and negative terminals I used are these : http://sparks.gogo.co.nz/AA_-18650-etc-Battery-Cell-Terminal-Pair-528.html but you can probably get them elsewhere too. They have a backplate which is 13.5mm wide and 11.5mm high (not including the leg), the spring is about 10.3mm extended (measured from back of backplate) and 3mm compressed fully. These terminals simply press into the provided slots.

Naturally you can put the terminals in any way you wish, series, parallel, whatever, the positioning and wiring of the terminals is your business.

The catch and lid retail the cells very strongly, I could not shake them out.

Attach Catch

After printing the 3 components, put a drop of CA glue (cyanoacrylate / superglue) on the underside of the lid where you will see a small indentation that the catch is to be attached to. Clamp the catch on until the CA sets. You may find that the first time the catch isn't well glued, I find that the CA I use tends to wick into the PLA on the first application, so just add a fresh dot of glue and try again.

This was designed in OnShape you can view/copy it here
https://cad.onshape.com/documents/be6d5f907bc0e83693f00d8c/w/96e1eeaa962fd97433430fbb/e/0ab6ed65229181bc63db04a0

title: Orca 0.43 X-Plate mod (get rid of the front bar)

description.text:
This is my attempt to free up the front of the Orca 0.43 for a 40mm fan mount.  
UPDATE 25/11/2013 - New stl's uploaded, the parts now have a lip so that the M8 nuts / threaded bar pull on the correct face, rather than against the 'jigsaw' edge so you should be able to tighten the inside nuts up. Some dimensions have also been tweaked to fit better.  
Measurements are taken from the original x-plate, so everything should line up.

Drill the holes to 4.2mm, 8mm (for the frame rods), 8.2mm (for the smooth rods) and 3mm, (for the motor bolts)  
Remove the old x-plate (easiest to remove the x smooth rods and threaded bars, just loosen off the z-axis smooth rod clamps, as well as the z and x optos and the x motor).  
Attach the smooth rod clamps and the x-belt bearings to the new plates, then put the new 'plates' in (you'll probably need to pry the sides apart a bit to get these in).  
Then run the threaded rod through from one side to the other adding nuts/washers as necessary.  
Make up two short lengths of threaded bar, (about 50mm each and secure the front of the 'plates' to each side.  
Refit the z-axis smooth rods, x-axis smooth rods (and stops/opto), x motor, and z-opto.  
Tension up the x-axis belt, and tweak the rear threaded rod to stop the belt wandering.  
PLEASE BE AWARE THIS IS A WIP. :-)

title: Replacement Bushing for Flux 3d Printer
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
As I was having trouble with the existing bushings on the Flux 3d printer, I made these replacements with the Flux itself.
Problem is described more in depth by others here:
http://forum.flux3dp.com/t/something-wrong-with-first-layer/1448

Getting them to work is a lot of trickery and might void warranty, so please use at your own risk and be prepared for trial and error, but I was tired of waiting for a solution and wanted the darn machine to work better. And now my printer is working a lot better.
Not as good as it can I think, but at least I can print again.

Make sure they are not too loose after printing (or you will the same issue as with the original ones), this also depends on print(er) quality.
If too loose, scale the file in X-Y by 99% or so, until you have one that fits tightly on 8mm rod.
I then slightly sanded the outside of the new bushings until they were nice and smooth and fit inside the existing housing.

For a tight yet smooth fit on the 8mm rod:
Take an old piece of 8mm steel rod, heat it with boiling water and slide the bushing on it. Let it cool or slide to cool part and it should be a nice fit.
On some this was not enough so I put some whitening toothpaste and water on the old rod.
(not the bleachy but the gritty kind, it polishes well)
Then either manually or with a cordless drill polish the inside of the bushing with the tooth-paste (thing layer) covered rod,until it runs smoothly.

You have to remove (part) of the top of the printer and the belts, to be able to remove the old bushing and place on the new.
But make sure they run smoothly individually before you re-assemble.
Also make sure they run smoothly in pair when built into the housing (no belt needed yet for this) before you re-assemble the rest. Sometime a slight twist on the rod for each bearing will make it nestle better.

If printed in PLA normally you do not really need any lubricant.
Stiction and friction is minimal enough and a lot of lubes dry out and increase friction or stiction in the long run.
Although I hear silicon lubes (bicycle spray did not work for me, dried up to gummy mess)
or lithium grease may help.

description.text:
This is a personalizable cup holder. I attached this to my client's lap tray on his wheelchair using a Stick and Suck Pad from RJ Cooper. The pad permanently sticks to the bottom of the cup holder and uses microscopic suction cups to temporarily attach to the lap tray or table top. It can be removed and reattached repeatedly.

-Link to stick and suck pads
https://www.rjcooper.com/stick-&-suck/index.html

You can edit the width and height of the cup holder and whether there is a handle slot or not. You can also include a name or message on the cup holder if you desire.

For the text string I used Write.scad. You will need this file as well as the text library to include personalization.
This file can be found here:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:16193

Note: I included the files for Write.scad and Letters.dxf but haven't been able to get text strings to appear in the customizer. If anyone knows how to correct this for the benefit of others, please comment and share.

title: Black Snapper 3D-Gimbal for GoPro Hero3+
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is a 3D-Gimbal for the Black Snapper. It is designed to hold a GoPro Hero3 and to use with small Emax 1806 450kv motors.

As controller board I use the Storm32 controller from banggood. The MPU fits perfect to the backside of the GoPro mount.
I also use a protection lens for the GoPro so that you can add a ND-filter to avoid jello.

There is a hole in arm_2 for the cables. I didn't put the cables through the hole because I tried different arms and didn't want to unplug the cables all the time from the board.
Print every part once. I used about 80%-90% infill to be stiff enough
